 Regent Quarterly Market Letter 
 Important Disclosure Information 





Market Letter
          2nd Quarter 2017

						The market’s strength continued during the second quarter.  Interest rates remain at low levels and fell further during the quarter.  This brings us back to TINA (There Is No Alternative), and TINA drives money into the stock market.  The economy slowed a bit during the first quarter to about a 1.5% annual growth rate, but it accelerated in the second quarter to about 2.5%.  Commodity prices were weak during Q2 which caused the stock market to worry less about interest rate increases.                     
				  


 
Q2, 2017
2017 YTD


S&P500 
3.1%
  9.3%


Dow Jones
4.0%
  9.4%


NASDAQ
4.2%
14.7%


Foreign markets generally outperformed the U.S. during the second quarter.  Europe was the best performer (VGK gained 8.4% during Q2) and Brazil was the worst (EWZ fell 8.1%)


Q2, 2017 Review
Technology stocks were strong during the second quarter, with the NASDAQ once again outperforming the S&P500 and the Dow Jones Industrial Average.  People talk about FAANG (Facebook, Apple, Amazon, Netflix and Google), and these and similar stocks have paced the market all year.  For the year, Facebook is up 31%; Apple is up 25%; Amazon is up 29%; Netflix is up 21%; and Google is up 17%.             
                        
                        Healthcare stocks were very strong during the second quarter.  Some of the fears about a healthcare bill faded.  The bill is not tough on drug pricing; it removes taxes on medical devices; and it is friendly to health insurance companies.  For the second quarter, Amgen increased 6%; Medtronic gained 10%; and United Healthcare increased 14%.  These are big leaders in their sub-sectors, but they are mostly representative of healthcare sector performance.  
                        
                        Energy stocks were the worst performers in the market with the XLE index falling 6.5%.  Iran, Iraq and Libya are all producing more oil, and U.S. production is booming.       
                        						                        
                        In our letter from the last quarter, we wrote about our inflation concerns, and we highlighted commodity prices.  Commodity prices had been strong, but they were broadly weaker in Q2.  Oil is the biggest component of commodity prices, and it fell again during Q2 - from $50.60 to $46.04.  Natural gas prices also fell during Q2.  Copper, Gold and Soy Bean prices were relatively unchanged; Corn and Wheat were up during Q2.
                        
                        Wages are still up almost 3% over the same time last year, but the fall in commodities caused the increase in the Consumer Price Index (CPI) to slow down.  The most recent CPI was up 1.9%, which is still below the Federal Reserve’s target inflation rate of 2.0%.  The unemployment rate ticked down 0.1% during the quarter to 4.3%.  The Federal Reserve increased interest rates by 0.25% in June, but given the reduction in inflation, the Federal Reserve may hold off in raising interest rates for the rest of this year. 
                        
                        Despite the rise in short–term interest rates, longer term rates declined, with the yield on the 10–year Treasury bond falling from 2.42% to 2.27%.  Financial stocks (XLF) were weak early in the quarter, but rallied strongly at the end of the quarter for a total increase of 4.4%.  
                        
                        The U.S. Dollar was weak during the second quarter.  Combined with better Q2 growth, this caused estimates for corporate profits (earnings) to increase.  The Price–to–Earnings ratio (P/E) for the market remains high at about 18.  This is higher than the long–term average.  If rates stay low and growth stays positive, TINA should remain in place and an 18 P/E is sustainable.  However, the higher the P/E gets, the higher the risk becomes if rates increase or if growth falters.  
                        
                        
                        
Q3, 2017 Investment Strategy
The 2016 election changed our view slightly.  Had Mrs. Clinton been elected, we expected a recession in 2017 or 2018.  The Trump administration is reducing regulations and generally helping businesses.  There are promises of foreign profits repatriation, lower tax rates and increased infrastructure spending.  The market is still giving the administration the benefit of doubt on these issues.  If enacted, these policies won’t stop the business cycle, but they are likely to extend it, and we are now planning for a later downturn in 2019 or 2020.  We became modestly more bullish after the election.  In Q2, we maintained this modestly bullish posture, and we plan the same for Q3.      
						
						We must remember that we are now over 8 years into this economic expansion that began in March, 2009.  The longest expansion in the history of the U.S. has been 10 years.  Although we became more bullish after the election, we remain aware that a downturn is still likely to be on the near–term horizon.  If the market continues to perform well and P/E ratios expand further, or if the Federal Reserve raises interest rates too much, we will move to a more defensive posture.    

						The Federal Reserve is now forecasting one additional rate increase in 2017 – taking the Federal Funds rate from the current 1.25% to 1.50%.  Since inflation has moderated recently, we think they may hold off on this rate increase.  The 2018 forecast is for 3 rate increases – for a total increase of 0.75%.  Growth will need to pick up for this to happen.   In addition to raising short-term interest rates, the Federal Reserve also plans to shrink its balance sheet (i.e. own less bonds and mortgages).  In the last few years, the Fed has been increasing its balance sheet (Quantitative Easing) to keep interest rates artificially low.  Starting later this year, they plan to stop buying bonds and mortgages and to potentially begin selling them.  The Fed moving from a buyer to a seller should have the effect of increasing interest rates.

                        With growth continuing and with the Fed removing accommodation, we expect interest rates to rise later this year and next year.  The interest rate on the 10–year Treasury bond is currently about 2.3%.  We expect that it will rise to 2.5% – 3.0% this year and perhaps as high as 3.5% – 4.0% in 2018/2019.  If this happens, we doubt the economy can handle rates this high, and this could be the trigger for a 2019 or 2020 recession.  
                        
                        It’s also possible that the next downturn could be triggered by a geopolitical event.  North Korea is probably the most concerning.  Between Kim Jong–un and Donald Trump you would be hard pressed to find more potentially volatile adversaries.  A confrontation with North Korea would definitely affect South Korea, Japan and China.  These are more than big enough to matter and could cause real damage to our economy.
                                               
                        
                  		

                    IMPORTANT DISCLOSURE INFORMATION:  Historical performance results for investment indices and/or categories are calculated including reinvestment of dividends and other income.  These results have been provided for general comparison purposes only, and generally do not reflect the deduction of transaction and/or custodial charges, the deduction of an investment management fee, nor the impact of taxes, the incurrence of which would have the effect of decreasing historical performance results.  It should not be assumed that your account holdings correspond directly to any comparative indices.                    
                    

